For your raw-HTML playground, I would give it this shape:

Interpretation gear
Raw HTML becomes a semantic tree inside the browser VM. That is the parse5 part, plus the JS walk that turns nodes into something your browser logic can reason about. In your repo this lives mainly in browser.mjs:808 and uses parse5 directly there, not in Rust. This is the “what is this document?” gear.

Realization gear
This is the bigger middle gear: CSS resolution, box intent, and layout. I would not split this into two top-level gears unless you really want a finer model.

lightningcss is mostly a parsing/normalization accelerator behind the style system, via css.mjs:1 and the native bridge in lightningcss_native.rs:138
Yoga is the constraint solver that takes the JS-built row/interactive model and computes positions/sizes, in browser.mjs:899 and yoga_native.rs:406
So if you were picturing “1 gear for parse5 and 1 gear for lightning + yoga”, that is close, but I would tighten it to:

parse/meaning
style+layout realization
because lightning and yoga are not peers in the same way parse5 is. parse5 creates the world. lightningcss and Yoga help realize that world into renderable structure.

Hosting/scheduling gear
This is the runtime chassis, not the browser semantics. The browser task owns one QJS VM, feeds it HTML/input/RPC/viewport/scroll, pumps pending JS jobs, and renders every tick. That loop is in browser_task.rs:1449. The generic VM pump is in vm.rs:105. This is where embassy matters.
On your “QJS workers vs embassy tasks” question, the correct mental split is:

embassy task = scheduling lane
QJS VM = one isolated JS world
QJS worker = a pattern where another embassy task owns another QJS VM
That worker model is explicit in workers.rs:468. So workers are not an alternative to embassy. They are embassy-scheduled extra VMs.

If I compress the whole thing to the most honest 3-gear model for your system, it is:

DOM meaning gear: parse5 + JS tree walk
document realization gear: CSS resolve + Yoga layout + row/interactive synthesis
runtime gear: embassy-driven VM pump, IO, RPC, rendering, optional worker isolation
One extra nuance that matters here: assets are almost a side-channel, not one of the main gears. Your page-state code separates “document rendered enough to draw” from “all assets complete” in browser_page_state.mjs:1. That is a nice sign that your pipeline is really document-first, asset-second.

